{
  "doc_id": "39883",
  "text": "MEG has already shown promise in terms of detecting AD in its earliest clinical stage (see [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] ). One study of 15 AD patients localized the generators of focal magnetic slow waves during an eyes-open resting condition using a simple dipole model [CITATION_3] . There was an increase in the number of dipoles in the delta and theta bands, and significant slowing in brain electrical activity in the temporal and parietal regions of both hemispheres of the AD patients [CITATION_4] . Critically, the slow-wave activity in the right temporal parietal regions varied as a function of degree of cognitive impairment, whereas the activity in the left temporal areas was associated with functional status [CITATION_5] . The alterations in brain function that are detected with MEG, especially those in the temporal regions, are significantly correlated with the relative volume of the lateral and medial temporal lobes [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] . This establishes a link between altered brain structure and altered brain function measured in two different modalities (i.e., MRI and MEG).",
